As of 13th December 6,092 deaths had been registered which mentioned COVID-19
The highest number of COVID-19 deaths were registered in week 17 (20th to 26th April). Deaths are now falling again after a rise between weeks 38 and 46 (14th September to 15th November).
Most excess deaths have occurred among the older population
Between weeks 12 and 50 (16th March to 13th December) there were 2,521 (19%) more deaths in the 85+ age group than average.

In the same period, there were 1,920 excess deaths in the 75-84 age group (16% above average), 961 excess deaths in the 65-74 age group (13% above average), 824 excess deaths in the 45-64 (14% above average), and 177 excess deaths in the 15-44 age group (11% above average).
Between the same weeks, there were 19 (-11%) fewer deaths than average for the 0-14 age group.

flowRoot.flowPara: QUICK START GUIDE
- Save this template to:
P:\DIVISION WIDE\Data Visualisation and Infographics\Secure area
- Choose a layout:
1 page = left
2 pages = left and right
3 pages = 2 lefts and a right
- Update the header and footer
- Remove the National Statistics logo if needed
- Update the colour of the section line dividers (the horizontal dotted lines) to the main colour of your infographic.
- Create chart(s) in R and export as SVG with ggsave. Import into Inkscape (File > Import or Ctrl+I).
- Save a copy as PDF with File -> Save a copy (Shift + Ctrl + Alt + S). Choose 300 dpi.
- Combine multiple pages into a single file with the professional version of Adobe Acrobat.
- After publication, zip all files and save them to the infographics folder in eRDM.
- Delete the files in: P:\DIVISION WIDE\Data Visualisation and Infographics\Secure area
- Imported charts come in a bit 'funny'
-- Try ungrouping and then grouping - this sometimes fixes issues with importing charts.
- Exporting to PNG includes objects outside the canvas
-- Change export area to drawing
- Can't copy/paste from another Inkscape file
-- This is a bug. Duplicate and cut instead.
- The colour/transparency of an object changed for no reason
-- Inkscape likes to change the fill of objects to linear gradients when you're not looking. Change the fill back to solid.
QA CHECKLIST
- Data
- Text
-- SMOG score
-- Font, size, weight
-- Colour
-- Consider direct annotation
- Colour
-- Headers and footers
-- Horizontal dotted lines
- Alignment
-- Numbers right aligned
-- Text left aligned
-- Shaded areas on the correct sides
- Spelling and grammar (Ctrl + Alt + K)
- Accessibility
-- Print in black and white
-- Contrast ratios
-- Correct reading order for screen readers
- Usability
-- Show it to someone unfamiliar with the topic
TROUBLESHOOTING INKSCAPE
The shaded areas should to be facing outside when printed - so alternate the left and right templates.
- For other type of content you might want to design alternative layouts. For example the middle template might work for a single large chart.
Use the same design style: white background for charts and visuals and shaded background for commentary. Use dotted lines to divide space into smaller sections.
If you create an alternative layout, think about the new margins and create your own guide lines as well. You might want to update the template with the new layout.

- For each infographic use only one theme colour and complement it with neutral colours. Make sure that visual elements to encode different categories (bars, lines or other type of charts) are distinguishable from each other even in black and white. If colour is not enough, use other attributes, such as line thickness or pattern. Don’t rely only on colour (hue) to encode information.
- Edit your chart as much as you can in R (or Excel) before you import it into Inkscape. This saves repeating work when data changes or when you get feedback.

If you prefer MS Excel, after you create your chart in MS Excel, paste it in MS PowerPoint and save it as an Enhanced Windows Metafile (.emf). Then import it into Inkscape as before. This way you will import a vector graphic object and not a bitmap object. However, depending on the type of chart you are using it could be difficult to edit with Inkscape.
- Don't use save as because this leaves the PDF open in Inkscape (so you might continue working on it thinking it's an SVG file and then not be able to save your changes).
